'''''Agaricus bernardii''''', commonly called the '''salt-loving mushroom''', is an [[agaric]] fungus  in the family [[Agaricaceae]]. A short, squat mushroom, the thick [[stipe (mycology)|stem]] is usually less than the diameter of the cap, which ranges from {{convert|5|<U+2013>|15|cm|in|abbr=on}}. Found in Asia, Europe, North America, and New Zealand, it is a [[Halotolerance|salt-tolerant]] species that grows in salt marshes, dunes, and coastal grassland. The fungus produces [[basidiocarp|fruit bodies]] ([[mushroom]]s) with convex to flattened [[pileus (mycology)|caps]] up to {{convert|15|cm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter, atop thick [[stipe (mycology)|stems]] up to {{convert|10|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. The cap surface is whitish to [[buff (color)|buff]], and can develop  scales or warts in age. [[lamella (mycology)|Gills]] are initially pink before turning brown when the [[spore]]s mature. The [[trama (mycology)|flesh]] turns reddish when it is cut or bruised. The mushroom somewhat resembles ''[[Agaricus bitorquis]]'' but it differs from that species by the reddish-brown staining of cap and stem tissue, the nature of the [[annulus (mycology)|ring]] on the stem, as well as its briny odor. An [[edible mushroom]], it is stronger in flavor but similar to the store-bought button mushrooms, ''[[Agaricus bisporus]]''.

==Taxonomy==
The species was first [[species description|described]] by French mycologist [[Lucien Qu<U+00E9>let]] as ''Psalliota bernardi'' in 1879, based on collections made in [[La Rochelle]], a seaport on the [[Bay of Biscay]] (France).<ref name="Qu<U+00E9>let 1878"/> [[Pier Andrea Saccardo]] transferred it to ''[[Agaricus]]'' in 1887. [[Synonym (taxonomy)|Synonyms]] include ''Psalliota bernardii'', ''Pratella bernardii'', ''Fungus bernardii'', and ''Agaricus campestris'' subsp. ''bernardii''.<ref name="urlMycoBank: Agaricus bernardii"/>

The infrageneric (below genus-level) [[classification (biology)|classification]] of ''A.&nbsp;bernardii'' is not known with certainty. In his 1978 proposed classification, [[Paul Heinemann]] placed it in the subsection ''Bitorques'' of the [[section (biology)|section]] ''Agaricus''.<ref name="Heinemann 1978"/>  Although the species has some similarities with species in the [[section (biology)|section]] ''Duploannulatae'' based on the structure of its [[partial veil|veil]] and its tendencies towards rufescence (developing a red coloration), [[molecular phylogenetic|molecular]] analysis shows that it does not belong in this section.<ref name="Challen 2003"/><ref name="Kerrigan 2008"/> An earlier (1999) analysis suggested that it is closely related to the "Agaricus clade", which contains ''[[Agaricus subperonatus|A.&nbsp;subperonatus]]'', ''[[Agaricus devoniensis|A.&nbsp;devoniensis]]'', ''[[Agaricus bisporus|A.&nbsp;bisporus]]'', ''[[Agaricus spissicaulis|A.&nbsp;spissicaulis]]'', ''[[Agaricus bitorquis|A.&nbsp;bitorquis]]'', and ''[[Agaricus impudicus|A.&nbsp;impudicus]]''.<ref name="Mitchell 1999b"/> In 1986, [[Henri Romagnesi]] placed it in section ''Chitonioides'';<ref name="Romagnesi 1986"/> Solomon Wasser demoted this to a subsection of ''Duploannulatae'' in 1995,<ref name="Wasser 1995"/> and later provided molecular support for his decision. In addition to ''A.&nbsp;bernardii'', species in Wasser's concept of subsection ''Chitonioides'' include ''[[Agaricus rollanii|A.&nbsp;rollanii]]'', ''[[Agaricus bernardiiformis|A.&nbsp;bernardiiformis]]'', ''[[Agaricus gennadii|A.&nbsp;gennadii]]'', ''[[Agaricus pequinii|A.&nbsp;pequinii]]'', and ''[[Agaricus nevoi|A.&nbsp;nevoi]]''.<ref name="Didukh 2005"/>

The species was named after the original collector, G.&nbsp;Bernard.<ref name="Qu<U+00E9>let 1878"/> ''Agaricus bernardii'' is [[common name|commonly]] known as the salt-loving mushroom.<ref name="Roberts 2011"/>

==Description==
[[File:Agaricus bernardii 2377.jpg|thumb|left|The gills are free from attachment to the stem, and crowded closely together.]]
[[Basidiocarp|Fruit bodies]] of ''Agaricus bernardii'' have [[pileus (mycology)|caps]] that range in shape from convex to flattened, and reach a diameter of {{convert|5|<U+2013>|15|cm|in|abbr=on}}. The cap surface is dry and smooth, with a white or buff color that can develop brownish spots in maturity. In age, the surface often forms scales or warts. The [[trama (mycology)|flesh]] is thick, firm, and stains reddish-orange or reddish-brown when cut, although this reaction can be slow to develop.<ref name="Mitchell 1999"/> Its odor ranges from mild to briny to pungent.<ref name="Arora 1986"/> The [[lamella (mycology)|gills]] are free from attachment to the stem, and packed close together. Initially grayish-pink to pinkish, they turn reddish-brown and then chocolate brown as the spores mature. The [[stipe (mycology)|stem]] is solid (i.e., not hollow), firm, and measures {{convert|4|<U+2013>|10|cm|in|abbr=on}} long by {{convert|2|<U+2013>|4|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} thick. A thick, white, rubbery [[partial veil]] covers the gills of the immature mushroom, and eventually remains as a [[annulus (mycology)|ring]] on the middle of the stem.<ref name="Mitchell 1999"/>

Although the mushrooms sometimes have an odor that is briny or pungent ("though not inappropriate"<ref name="Roberts 2011"/>), they are [[edible mushroom|edible]] and good.<ref name="Davis 2012"/> [[David Arora]] compares its taste to that of the closely related ''Agaricus bitorquis'', "but a little chewier and sometimes with a slightly salty or briny taste."<ref name="Arora 1986"/>

''Agaricus bernardii'' mushrooms produce a dark brown [[spore print]]. The [[spore]]s are smooth, broadly elliptical, and have dimensions of 6<U+2013>7.5 by 5<U+2013>6&nbsp;[[micrometre|<U+03BC>m]].<ref name="Arora 1986"/> The [[basidia]] (spore-bearing cells) are four-spored and club-shaped, measuring 14<U+2013>25 by 4<U+2013>7&nbsp;<U+03BC>m; the [[sterigmata]] are 4<U+2013>5&nbsp;<U+03BC>m. Cheilocystidia ([[cystidia]] on the gill edge) are broadly club-shaped to cylindrical, [[hyaline]] (translucent), and measure 17<U+2013>30 by 4<U+2013>8&nbsp;<U+03BC>m.<ref name="Mitchell 1999"/>

===Similar species===
[[File:Agaricus.bitorquis.nathan.jpg|thumb|right|''Agaricus bitorquis'' is a lookalike species.]]
''[[Agaricus bitorquis]]'', also edible, has a similar appearance, but can be distinguished by its double ring, and the lack of a fishy or briny odor. Additionally, ''A.&nbsp;bitorquis'' does not stain reddish when cut, and usually does not have a scaly or warty cap.<ref name="Arora 1986"/> The Hungarian species ''[[Agaricus bernardiiformis|A.&nbsp;bernardiiformis]]'', named for its similarity to ''A.&nbsp;bernardii'', is distinguished from the latter by its smaller spores (6.2<U+2013>8.2 by 5.4<U+2013>6.2&nbsp;<U+03BC>m) and its club-shaped cheilocystidia that measure 17<U+2013>35 by 7<U+2013>9.5&nbsp;<U+03BC>m.<ref name="Didukh 2005"/> [[MycoBank]], however, considers the two species to be [[conspecific]].<ref name="urlMycoBank: Agaricus bernardiiformis"/>

==Habitat and distribution==
''Agaricus bernardii'' is a [[saprobic]] species.<ref name="urlMushroomExpert"/> Its mushrooms fruit singly, scattered, or in groups on the ground. They grow in sandy soils, lawns, and in habitats with a high salt concentration, like along ocean coasts and salt marshes.<ref name="Arora 1986"/> Once primarily a maritime species, the fungus has spread inland to roadside verges where salt has been applied to [[de-ice]] the roads.<ref name="Scott 1985"/><ref name="Roberts 2011"/> Fruit bodies sometimes form underground.<ref name="Arora 1986"/> Mushrooms can also grow in [[fairy ring]]s, especially when in grasslands or pastures.<ref name="Mitchell 1999"/> A Czech study determined that the mushrooms will strongly [[bioaccumulation|bioaccumulate]] silver from contaminated soil. Although the average concentration of silver in the soil is typically less than 1 milligram per kilogram of soil, it can be significantly elevated near industrial sites such as mines and smelters. The concentration of silver in the caps<U+2014>which reached levels of up to 544&nbsp;mg per kg of mushroom tissue ([[dry matter|dry weight]])<U+2014>was about twice that of the stems.<ref name="Borovi<U+010D>ka 2010"/>

The species is found in Asia, Europe, North America<ref name="Roberts 2011"/> (including Mexico)<ref name="Perez-Silva 1986"/> and New Zealand.<ref name="Mitchell 1999"/>

